==Māna (head mudras)==
Māna mudras are an important part of Kundalini yoga, and many are important meditation techniques in their own right. {| class="wikitable" |- ! Name in Sanskrit ! Translation(s) in English ! Other Meanings ! Illustration |- |Shambhavi Mudra |Eyebrow centre gazing with eyes half-open | | |- |Nasikagra Drishti |Nosetip gazing | | |- |Khechari Mudra |Tongue lock | | |- |Kaki mudra |The crow's beak | | |- |Bhujangini Mudra |Cobra respiration | | |- |Bhoochari Mudra |Gazing into nothingness | | |- |Akashi mudra |Awareness of inner space | | |- |Shanmukhi mudra |Closing the seven gates | | |- |Unmani Mudra |The attitude of mindlessness | | |}
==Kaya (postural mudras)==
