{{Infobox person |name = Masaharu Taniguchi |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = {{birth date|1893|11|22|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Kobe]] |death_date = {{death date and age|1985|7|17|1893|11|22|df=y}} |death_place = [[Nagasaki, Nagasaki|Nagasaki]] |death_cause = |resting_place = [[Tama Cemetery]], Fuchu, Japan |resting_place_coordinates = |nationality = Japanese |other_names = 谷口雅春 |known_for = Founding [[Seicho-no-ie]] |education = |alma_mater = [[University of Waseda]] |spouse = Teruko Taniguchi }} {{NewThought}} {{nihongo|'''Masaharu Taniguchi'''|谷口 雅春|Taniguchi Masaharu|22 November 1893 &ndash; 17 June 1985}} was a [[Japan]]ese [[New Thought]] leader, founder of [[Seicho-no-ie]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Japanese New Religions: In Global Perspective|editor=Clark, Peter B.|publisher=Curzon|location=Surrey, UK|year=2000|pages=35, 48|isbn=0-7007-1185-6}}</ref>
He began studying [[English literature]] at the [[University of Waseda]], Tokyo. In parallel, he also studied the works of [[Fenwicke Holmes]], and subsequently translated Holmes' book, ''[[The Law of Mind in Action]]'' into Japanese. In 1929, after much study and contemplation, he reported having received a [[divine revelation]] followed by the healing of his daughter. This led in 1930 to the creation of a magazine, ''Seicho-no-ie'' ("home of infinite life, wisdom, and abundance"). The movement grew during the 1930s, although was suppressed during World War II. In 1952, he co-authored a book with [[Fenwicke Holmes]] titled ''[[The Science of Faith]]''.<ref name=Gale>"Masaharu Taniguchi." ''Religious Leaders of America, 2nd ed.'', edited by J. Gordon Melton. Detroit: The Gale Group, 1999. Reproduced in Biography Resource Center. Farmington Hills, Mich.: Gale, 2008.</ref>
Taniguchi died in a Nagasaki hospital on June 17, 1985, at the age of ninety-one.<ref>{{cite news |title=Religious leader Taniguchi |author=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Montreal Gazette]] |date=1985-06-18 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3H0xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=2qUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5839,3948635 |accessdate=2010-01-07}}</ref>
